   "source": [
    "missing_target_rows = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for col in train.columns:\n",
    "    if col == TARGET:\n",
    "        continue\n",
    "\n",
    "    missing_flag = train[col].isna()\n",
    "\n",
    "    if missing_flag.sum() > 0:\n",
    "        missing_target_rows.append({\n",
    "            \"column\": col,\n",
    "            \"missing_count\": int(missing_flag.sum()),\n",
    "            \"missing_pct\": missing_flag.mean() * 100,\n",
    "            \"transported_rate_when_missing\": train.loc[missing_flag, TARGET].mean(),\n",
    "            \"transported_rate_when_not_missing\": train.loc[~missing_flag, TARGET].mean(),\n",
    "            \"absolute_rate_difference\": abs(\n",
    "                train.loc[missing_flag, TARGET].mean() - train.loc[~missing_flag, TARGET].mean()\n",
    "            )\n",
    "        })\n",
    "\n",
    "missing_target_analysis = (\n",
    "    pd.DataFrame(missing_target_rows)\n",
    "    .sort_values(\"absolute_rate_difference\", ascending=False)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "display(missing_target_analysis)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "75279cfd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 5 interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "Most columns in this dataset have relatively small missing percentages. The missingness comparison checks whether rows with missing values have a very different transported rate from rows without missing values. If the difference is small, missingness is probably not a strong signal by itself. Even so, missing values must still be handled before modelling, so the preprocessing pipeline later imputes numerical values with the median and categorical values with the most frequent category."
   ]
  },
